{"/service/ndnp/mnhi/batch_mnhi_iago_ver01/data/sn83016844/00542865349/1949021001/1081.xml":{"full_text":"P\u00bbge Two\nTwin City Observer\nBex 95, 'T-n\u2014rrtt States. Miaaeapete IX Minn.\natlitM G. WUBaaaa Owner and Futtisaer\nMlites G. WUBaaaa Editor\nEARL SIMS. Advertence PL 2835\nESTYR BRADLEY PEAKE St. Paul Representative\n854 I\u00abkhart Avenue Dale 8825\nMART KYLE Mmaeapobs Representative\n3437 4th Ave So __ LOcust 7850\nALLIE B GLENN Circulation\u2014Advertising\nEntered as \u00bb<ond class matter March 8. 1945, at the post office at\nMinneapolis 1. Minnesota, under Act of March 3. 1879.\n-flcrrv bTMmb\nEDITORIAL\nIt is just as d.Sicult for city residents to look at things from\nthe farmer\u2019s viewpoint a.s it is for the farmer to understand\nthe problems of those who live in the cities.\nBut it isn\u2019t too d.fhcult for us to understand the position\nthe farmer is in a* he suddenly discovers that the prices he re-/\nceives for his products are suffering *harp reductions\u2014reduc\ntions, it is needless to say. much faster and much greater than\nthose which the consumer yet has to pay.\nThe farmer is in the *ame position that a man who works\nfor a wage or salary uld be in if he were to be informed when\nhe starts to work netx Monday that his wage or salary, effec\ntive right then, would be reduced 10, 15, or 20 per cent or even\nmore.\nIf that happened to you, you would do some howling, would\nyou not? If you were a farmer you likewise would have reason\nto become alarmed when payment for your labor is reduced con-1\nderably. Espec.ally ,f during the past year you had paid high I\nprxt* for the machinery, equipment, feed and other things you\nrid to rare to make a crop.\nJr view of tae .nflaDon spiral that continued wthout letup\nfor a naxbtr of year*, a 'break\u201d in prices was inevitable.' Off-\nhaad. perhaps Ai* a good th.ng that the break has come now in\niread of a year hence, when the breaking point would probably\nhave been cona^ierabiy higher.\nAfter all, it has always been true that the greater the fall\nthe harder the bump.\nHigh prices for raw farm products have been only partially\nresponsible for the unreasonably high prices that the consum\ner, and the farmer is a consumer as well as a producer, has had\nto pay. Where margin of markup or profit has been figured on\na percentage basis by the manufacturer, the packer, the proces\nsor, the jobber, wholesaler and retailer, that has meant that the\nfinal retail price of the completed commodity has gone far be\nyond the increase represented by the original good price for the\nraw material or commodity.\nNow, the break has come about without any doubt. Farmers\nwho in the past have been the earliest and chief sufferers from\na depression, panic or recession of business, can not be blamed\nfor objecting to playing the role of \u201cgoat\u201d every time. They are\nentitled to some measure of protection and certainly it appears\nthey will receive it.\nBut \u201cprotection\u201d should not extend to a price support pro\ngram that will encourage maximum productivity principally\nfor the purpose of profiting from a price support program that\nmeans easy pickings.\nOn the other hand, with the farmer already taking a smaller\nmargin of profit, the way to safe stabilization of the economy\nseems to lie along a road in which other business and industry\nlikewise accepts a smaller margin or percentage of profit, and\nin which laltor does its share by abiding by its own expressed\nconviction that a lower retail price level is the equivalent of, and\npreferable to, another wage increase.\nCONSILT YOUR LAWYER BEFORE YO(\u2019 SIGN\nA bill to license real estate agents in Minnesota is causing\nconsiderable interest and discussion Whether this bill be\ncomes a law or not, the buyer or seller of real estate should i\nconsult his lawyer before signing any papers involving real\nestate.\nThe purchase of a home represents the largest investment\nthe average individual ever makes In many cases, it involves\nthe life time savings of the buyer. In the past. Twin City\nresidents have lost tens ot thousands of dollars because of\nTWIN CITY OBSERVER\nthe fraud of unscrupulous real estate agents, realtors and\notherwise.\nDishonest real estate agents often advise their \u201cclients\u201d\nthat it is a waste of time and money to consult a lawyer. In\nan effort to disarm their victims, they slander the entire legal\nprofession and impugn the ability and integrity of individual\nlawyers.\nActually, any individual who makes a real estate deal\nwithout the advice of his own lawyer is gambling. He is gam\nbling that everyone is honest and that he will npt be de\nfrauded. The small fee a lawyer charges is a trifle compared\nto the amount of money involved in the majority of real\nestate transactions.\nThe proposed bill to license real estate agents does not\ngive the public adequate protection. It should include a pro\nvision making all contracts affecting an interest in real estate\nvoid unless the parties thereto sign the same in the presence\nof their own lawyers. This provision will really protect the\nbuyers and sellers of real estate.\nWhatever the Legislature does, a good slogan for us all\nto remember is, \u201cFor the safety of your savings, consult\nyour lawyer before you sign papers of any kind.\u201d\nSunday, Feb. 6, wad Communion\nDay at Zion. Rev. H. W. Botts\npreached a spirited sermon taken\nfrom Ist Corinthians. 10 chapter,\n13 verse. Rev. E. J. Henderson,\nRev. F. Warder assisted in the\nservice. Music was rendered by\nthe Senior Choir and Junior Choir.\nf&UFb\n/M&rt most wkms\nFin\u00ae blended whiskey\u2014 90 5 prool 60X gram neutral torr n Fronkfort DiMUhrt Carp.. New York City\nUnited with us: Mrs. S. Jackson\not Humboldt Heights.\nVisitors in the morning service:\nRaymond Lindsay. Jessie Baker.\nRemember the sick and shut-In,\nMis. E. Fowler in Swedish Hospi\ntal. Remember her with cards.\nMrs. P. Bull in General Hospital\nNext time you\u2019re buying\nwe cordially invite you to say:\n\"Four Roses, please.\"\nYou\u2019ll find that this\nmatchless whiskey \u2014so mellow.\nso distinctive in flavor\nmakes a drink\nthat is truly magnificent.\nThursday, February 10, 1949\nDon't forget teacher meeting\nand prayer meeting every Wed\nnesday evening. You are always\nwelcome to Zion.\nMrs. L. Seaton, Reporter\nRev. H. W. Botts, Pastor\nFUNERAL SERVICES HELD\nFOR MARTILLA REDDICK\nMrs. Martilia L. Reddick of\n510 Humboldt avenue No., died\nat Minneapolis General Hospi\ntal Monday, Feb. 7th. Funeral\nservices were held Thursday,\nFeb. 10th from the Church of\nGod in Christ, with Rev. H. P.\nBuford officiating. Interment\nElmhurst cemetery. Survived\nby her husband, Rev. Hender\nson Reddick, and mother Dur\nant. Woodard\u2019s Funeral Home\nin charge of arrangements.\nCOMING! Basie Givens and his\ncelebrated Orchestra, Playing\nand Dancing, Labor lempte,\n117 S.E. 4th St. Monday, Feb.\n21, 1949.\nBest Talking Panel\nAfrican parrot Is said tn be the\nbest talker.\nwhiskey","height":"19842","width":"14556"}}
